.TH PACKET_GEN 1 "2026-04-18" "tsn-gen 0.0.1" "TSN Generator Tools"
.\" ====================================================================
.SH NAME
.\" ====================================================================
packet_gen \- generate, transmit, and decode IEEE 1722.1 / ADP packets
driven by YAML protocol definitions
.\" ====================================================================
.SH SYNOPSIS
.\" ====================================================================
.B packet_gen
\fB\-\-yaml\-dir\fR \fIdir\fR
{ \fB\-\-interface\fR \fIname\fR | \fB\-\-connect\fR \fIA:B\fR[\fI:C\&...\fR] | \fB\-\-stack\fR \fIA:B\fR[\fI:C\&...\fR] }
[\fIoptions\fR]
.PP
.B packet_gen
\fB\-\-yaml\-dir\fR \fIdir\fR
\fB\-\-list\-interfaces\fR
.PP
.B packet_gen
\fB\-\-yaml\-dir\fR \fIdir\fR
\fB\-\-interface\fR \fIname\fR
\fB\-\-decode\fR
{ \fB\-\-hex\fR \fIhexstring\fR | \fB\-\-transport\fR \fIspec\fR }
.\" ====================================================================
.SH DESCRIPTION
.\" ====================================================================
\fBpacket_gen\fR reads a directory of YAML protocol definition files,
builds an in\-memory database of protocol variables and interfaces, then
generates raw packet byte buffers whose field values are constrained by
the definitions.
.PP
Generated packets can be written to standard output in JSON or hex
format, and optionally delivered to a physical or simulated transport
backend: a Linux AF_PACKET raw socket, a libpcap\-format capture file,
or a Verilator RTL DUT via AXI\-Stream beats over a UNIX domain socket.
.PP
Three operating modes are available:
.TP
\fBGeneration mode\fR (default)
Build one or more packets from a single interface (\fB\-\-interface\fR),
a chained command/response exchange (\fB\-\-connect\fR), or a
concatenated multi\-layer frame (\fB\-\-stack\fR).
.TP
\fBDecode mode\fR (\fB\-\-decode\fR)
Receive raw bytes from a transport or a hex string on the command line
and decode them back to named field values using the declared interface.
.TP
\fBDiscovery mode\fR (\fB\-\-list\-interfaces\fR)
Parse the YAML directory and print all discovered interface names, then
exit.
.\" ====================================================================
.SH OPTIONS
.\" ====================================================================
.SS Required
.TP
\fB\-\-yaml\-dir\fR \fIpath\fR
Directory containing protocol YAML files.
The directory is walked recursively; every \fI.yaml\fR file whose
top\-level key is \fBservice:\fR is loaded.
Subdirectories are followed up to a maximum depth of 30.
.IP
To load a single protocol, point at its directory:
.br
\fIprotocols/application/1722_1/aecp\fR
.IP
To load all protocols (needed for \fB\-\-stack\fR across layers):
.br
\fIprotocols/\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-interface\fR \fIqualified\-name\fR
Fully qualified interface name of the form
\fI<service>::<ENTITY>::<INTERFACE>\fR.
Required unless \fB\-\-connect\fR, \fB\-\-stack\fR, or
\fB\-\-list\-interfaces\fR is given.
Run \fB\-\-list\-interfaces\fR to discover valid names in a directory.
.SS Generation options
.TP
\fB\-\-count\fR \fIn\fR
Number of packets (or rounds for \fB\-\-connect\fR / \fB\-\-stack\fR) to
generate.
Default: \fB1\fR.
Use \fB0\fR for an unlimited stream; interrupt with Ctrl\-C.
.TP
\fB\-\-seed\fR \fIn\fR
Seed the internal Mersenne\-Twister PRNG with the given 64\-bit unsigned
integer.
Identical seeds produce identical packet sequences, which is useful for
reproducible fuzzing and regression tests.
Default: seeded from \fI/dev/urandom\fR.
.TP
\fB\-\-output\fR \fBhex\fR|\fBjson\fR
Format for packets written to standard output.
Default: \fBjson\fR.
.RS
.TP
\fBhex\fR
One lower\-case hex string per line, no delimiters or whitespace.
.TP
\fBjson\fR
One JSON object per line (newline\-delimited JSON).
Single interface:
.nf
{"fields":{"message_type":0,"status":0,...},"hex":"1402422e..."}
.fi
Chained (\fB\-\-connect\fR): a JSON array, one object per stage.
Stacked (\fB\-\-stack\fR):
.nf
{"hex":"<all layers>","layers":[{"iface":"...","fields":{...},"hex":"..."},...]}
.fi
.RE
.TP
\fB\-\-transport\fR \fIspec\fR
Deliver each generated packet to the named backend in addition to
writing to standard output.
Default: \fBnone\fR.
See
.B TRANSPORT BACKENDS
below.
.TP
\fB\-\-connect\fR \fIA\fR:\fIB\fR[:\fIC\fR\&...]
Chain two or more interfaces into a single round.
In each round, packet A is generated first; fields that B declares
without a hard constraint (\fBexpected.values\fR) are overridden with
A\(cqs values when they share the same name.
This propagation continues through subsequent stages.
.IP
Typical use: simulate a command/response exchange where the responder
echoes \fIsequence_id\fR, \fItarget_entity_id\fR,
\fIcontroller_entity_id\fR, etc.
.IP
Multiple \fB\-\-connect\fR flags append to the same chain.
If \fB\-\-interface\fR is also given, it is prepended as stage\~0.
.IP
\fB\-\-connect\fR and \fB\-\-stack\fR are mutually exclusive.
.TP
\fB\-\-stack\fR \fIA\fR:\fIB\fR[:\fIC\fR\&...]
Concatenate bytes from multiple protocol layers into a single on\-wire
frame.
Each interface is generated independently (no field propagation) and its
byte buffer is appended in declaration order.
.IP
Typical use: assemble a complete Ethernet frame with protocol layers
stacked in network order (MAC header, AVTP control, AECP PDU).
.IP
JSON output includes both a top\-level \fB"hex"\fR with all layers
combined and a \fB"layers"\fR array with per\-layer detail.
.IP
\fB\-\-stack\fR and \fB\-\-connect\fR are mutually exclusive.
.SS Decode options
.TP
\fB\-\-decode\fR
Switch to decode mode.
Incoming bytes are sliced into fields using the declared interface(s)
and printed in the format selected by \fB\-\-output\fR.
Combine with \fB\-\-hex\fR for a single one\-shot decode, or with
\fB\-\-transport\fR to read from a live source.
.TP
\fB\-\-hex\fR \fIhexstring\fR
Decode a single packet supplied as a lower\-case hex string on the
command line.
Implies \fB\-\-decode\fR.
.SS Discovery
.TP
\fB\-\-list\-interfaces\fR
Parse \fB\-\-yaml\-dir\fR and print every discovered interface name with
its direction (\fIin\fR or \fIout\fR), then exit with code 0.
.SS Miscellaneous
.TP
\fB\-\-help\fR
Print a usage summary to standard error and exit with code 0.
.\" ====================================================================
.SH TRANSPORT BACKENDS
.\" ====================================================================
Specified with \fB\-\-transport\fR \fIkind\fR:\fIparam\fR.
.TP
\fBnone\fR
No transport; packets are written to standard output only.
This is the default.
.TP
\fBraw:\fR\fIifname\fR
Inject packets directly onto a network interface using a Linux
\fBAF_PACKET\fR/\fBSOCK_RAW\fR socket.
Requires \fBCAP_NET_RAW\fR; run as root or grant the capability with
\fBsetcap cap_net_raw+ep\fR.
.IP
Example: \fBraw:eth0\fR
.TP
\fBpcap:\fR\fIfilepath\fR
Write a libpcap\-format capture file (\fBLINKTYPE_ETHERNET\fR, no
external libpcap dependency).
The file is created or truncated on open.
Compatible with Wireshark and tcpdump.
.IP
Example: \fBpcap:/tmp/aecp_capture.pcap\fR
.TP
\fBverilator:\fR\fIsocket\-path\fR
Send 64\-bit AXI\-Stream beats over a UNIX domain socket to a Verilator
DUT.
The socket must already exist before \fBpacket_gen\fR starts
(the simulation creates it).
Each packet is framed as a sequence of \fIAxiStreamBeat\fR structs
(tdata/tkeep/tlast).
.IP
Example: \fBverilator:/tmp/verilator_axis.sock\fR
.IP
For cycle\-accurate co\-simulation without a socket, use the SystemC
integration in
.IR sim/ .
See
.BR sim/README.md .
.\" ====================================================================
.SH OUTPUT FORMATS
.\" ====================================================================
.SS hex
One lower\-case hexadecimal string per packet on standard output.
No spacing or framing.
Suitable for piping into other tools.
.SS json
One JSON object per line (newline\-delimited JSON, also called NDJSON).
.PP
Single interface:
.nf
{"fields":{"message_type":0,"status":0,"control_data_length":44},"hex":"1402002c..."}
.fi
.PP
Chain (\fB\-\-connect\fR): one JSON array per round, each element is a
stage object with an additional \fB"iface"\fR key.
.PP
Stack (\fB\-\-stack\fR): top\-level keys are \fB"hex"\fR (all bytes
concatenated) and \fB"layers"\fR (array of per\-layer objects).
.PP
Field values are decimal integers.
Fields appear in the order they are declared in the YAML \fBvars:\fR
section.
.\" ====================================================================
.SH INTERFACE NAMES
.\" ====================================================================
Interface names follow the convention:
.IP
\fI<service>\fR::\fI<ENTITY>\fR::\fI<INTERFACE>\fR
.PP
where \fI<service>\fR matches the \fBservice:\fR key at the top of the
YAML file, \fI<ENTITY>\fR is an entry under \fBentities:\fR, and
\fI<INTERFACE>\fR is an entry under that entity\(cqs \fBinterfaces:\fR
list.
.PP
Run \fB\-\-list\-interfaces\fR to enumerate all names available in a
given \fB\-\-yaml\-dir\fR.
.\" ====================================================================
.SH FIELD CONSTRAINTS
.\" ====================================================================
When a field\(cqs value is chosen during generation, the following
priority order applies:
.TP
1. \fBexpected.values\fR
A fixed list of allowed values.
One is chosen uniformly at random.
.TP
2. \fBexpected.range\fR
An inclusive [min, max] range.
A value is drawn uniformly.
.TP
3. \fBexpected.mask\fR
A bitmask.
A random value in [0, 2^\fIsize\fR\-1] is ANDed with the mask.
.TP
4. \fINo constraint\fR
A random value in [0, 2^\fIsize\fR\-1].
.\" ====================================================================
.SH EXIT STATUS
.\" ====================================================================
.TP
\fB0\fR
Success.
.TP
\fB1\fR
Argument error: bad option, missing required argument, or conflicting
flags.
.TP
\fB2\fR
Runtime error: YAML parse failure, interface not found, transport open
failed, or send/receive error.
.\" ====================================================================
.SH EXAMPLES
.\" ====================================================================
.SS Discovery
.TP
List all interfaces in the AECP protocol directory:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --list-interfaces
.fi
.SS Single\-interface generation
.TP
Generate one ACQUIRE_ENTITY packet in JSON format:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF
.fi
.TP
Generate 1000 packets in hex format with a fixed seed (reproducible fuzzing):
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --count 1000 --seed 42 --output hex
.fi
.TP
Stream packets continuously until Ctrl\-C:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_no_payload::AECP_NO_PAYLOAD::AECP_NO_PAYLOAD_IF \\
    --count 0
.fi
.TP
Extract a specific field value with jq:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --count 5 | jq '.fields.sequence_id'
.fi
.SS Transport delivery
.TP
Capture 50 VENDOR_UNIQUE PDUs to a pcap file:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_vendor_unique::AECP_VENDOR_UNIQUE::AECP_VENDOR_UNIQUE_IF \\
    --count 50 --transport pcap:/tmp/vendor_unique.pcap
.fi
.TP
Inject 10 ADP PDUs onto eth0 (requires root or CAP_NET_RAW):
.nf
sudo packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir parser/tests/test_resources/0020_adp_protocol_test \\
    --interface atdecc_adp_service::ADP_INTERFACE::ADP_IF_DATA \\
    --count 10 --transport raw:eth0
.fi
.TP
Send a packet to a Verilator DUT over a UNIX socket:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --transport verilator:/tmp/verilator_axis.sock
.fi
.SS Chained command/response (\-\-connect)
.TP
Simulate an ACQUIRE_ENTITY command/response exchange (5 rounds):
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --connect \\
        atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
       :atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --count 5
.fi
.IP
Fields shared by name (e.g. \fIsequence_id\fR, \fItarget_entity_id\fR)
are propagated from the command packet to the response.
.TP
Three-step chain \(em command, intermediate processing, response:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --connect CMD_IF:MID_IF:RSP_IF \\
    --count 10 --seed 7
.fi
.TP
Deliver chained packets to the DUT and also save a capture:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --connect \\
        atdecc_aecp_lock_entity::AECP_LOCK_ENTITY::AECP_LOCK_ENTITY_IF \\
       :atdecc_aecp_lock_entity::AECP_LOCK_ENTITY::AECP_LOCK_ENTITY_IF \\
    --count 20 --transport pcap:/tmp/lock_exchange.pcap
.fi
.SS Layer stacking (\-\-stack)
.TP
Assemble a complete IEEE 1722.1 AECP frame (Ethernet + AVTP + AECP = 55 bytes):
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols \\
    --stack \\
        ethernet_mac_frame::ETHERNET_FRAME::ETHERNET_FRAME_IF \\
       :avtp_control_header::AVTP_CONTROL::AVTP_CONTROL_IF \\
       :atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --count 3 --seed 42
.fi
.TP
Stack and inject onto the wire in one step:
.nf
sudo packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols \\
    --stack \\
        ethernet_mac_frame::ETHERNET_FRAME::ETHERNET_FRAME_IF \\
       :atdecc_adp_service::ADP_INTERFACE::ADP_IF_DATA \\
    --transport raw:eth0
.fi
.TP
Stack and write only the hex (no JSON envelope):
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols \\
    --stack \\
        ethernet_mac_frame::ETHERNET_FRAME::ETHERNET_FRAME_IF \\
       :avtp_control_header::AVTP_CONTROL::AVTP_CONTROL_IF \\
       :atdecc_aecp_set_stream_format::AECP_SET_STREAM_FORMAT::AECP_SET_STREAM_FORMAT_IF \\
    --output hex --count 100 --seed 1
.fi
.SS Decode mode
.TP
Decode a single hex packet directly on the command line:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --hex 1402002c000000000000000000000000
.fi
.TP
Decode all packets in a captured pcap file:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --decode --transport pcap:/tmp/aecp_capture.pcap
.fi
.TP
Decode live traffic from eth0 and filter by field with jq:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --decode --transport raw:eth0 | jq 'select(.fields.status != 0)'
.fi
.TP
Round\-trip: generate a packet then immediately decode it:
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --output hex --seed 99 | \\
xargs -I{} packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols/application/1722_1/aecp \\
    --interface atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --hex {}
.fi
.TP
Decode a multi\-layer stacked capture (Ethernet + AVTP + AECP):
.nf
packet_gen \\
    --yaml-dir protocols \\
    --stack \\
        ethernet_mac_frame::ETHERNET_FRAME::ETHERNET_FRAME_IF \\
       :avtp_control_header::AVTP_CONTROL::AVTP_CONTROL_IF \\
       :atdecc_aecp_acquire_entity::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY::AECP_ACQUIRE_ENTITY_IF \\
    --decode --transport pcap:/tmp/full_frame.pcap
.fi
.\" ====================================================================
.SH FILES
.\" ====================================================================
.TP
\fIprotocols/\fR
Default location for YAML protocol definitions shipped with tsn\-gen.
Pass a subdirectory to \fB\-\-yaml\-dir\fR to load only a subset.
.TP
\fIsim/\fR
SystemC co\-simulation integration (AxisBridge, VerilatorNetDevice,
sc_main).
See
.IR sim/README.md .
